\section{Quantum Error Correction Viewpoint: Codes, Capacities, and Correlated Noise}
\label{sec:qec}
\subsection{From HMC to Operator-Algebra QEC}
The joint $(I_n M_n)$ defines a protected subsystem whose logical information is adiabatically transferred into $R_{\le n}$ as $d_{M_n}$ shrinks (P0,P4). This fits naturally with operator-algebra QEC (OAQEC): the algebra of logical observables on $(I M)$ is preserved under the comb up to $O(1/S_{\rm BH})$ corrections and becomes reconstructible on sufficiently late radiation~(cf. OAQEC~\cite{KribsLaflammePoulin:2005}, approximate QEC~\cite{BenyOreshkov:2010}, general background in~\cite{NielsenChuang:2010}).

In Knill–Laflamme form~\cite{KnillLaflamme:1997}, errors $\{E_\alpha\}$ induced by memory-coupled emission satisfy
\begin{equation}
P_\mathcal{C}\, E_\alpha^\dagger E_\beta\, P_\mathcal{C} = c_{\alpha\beta}\, P_\mathcal{C} \ +\ \delta_{\alpha\beta}^{(\rm approx)}\,,
\end{equation}
with $P_\mathcal{C}$ the code projector on $(IM)$, and $\|\delta^{(\rm approx)}\|_1 = O(1/S_{\rm BH})$. The \emph{approximate} conditions follow from: (i) fast scrambling (P2) ensuring typicality, (ii) gentleness (P3) bounding local deviations, and (iii) adiabaticity (P4). A Petz (transpose) recovery or related OAQEC decoder achieves entanglement fidelity $F_e = 1 - O(1/S_{\rm BH})$ for diary-recovery on late radiation.

\subsection{Quantum Capacity with Memory and Decoupling}
The comb realizes a channel with \emph{memory}~\cite{KretschmannWerner:2005}, with a finite correlation time $\tau_{\rm mem}\sim \beta \log S_{\rm BH}$. For \emph{forgetful} memory channels (exponential decay of temporal correlations), quantum capacity admits single-letter characterizations or regularized limits in terms of coherent information~\cite{Devetak:2005}. Our decoupling proof (Sec.~\ref{sec:page_theorem}) gives an achievability bound: post-Page, the coherent information from $(IM)$ to radiation becomes positive and extensive; by concatenating late emissions across windows $W\gtrsim \tau_{\rm mem}/\Delta u$, one achieves reliable quantum transmission (diary recovery) with vanishing error in the large-$S_{\rm BH}$ limit.

\subsection{Quantum Error Correlations: Diagnostics and Impact}
Temporal non-Markovianity manifests as \emph{quantum error correlations} across emissions: $g^{(2)}(\Delta u)$ sidebands (Fig.~\ref{fig:g2}) and higher-order cumulants of the memory kernel. Such correlations can either assist or hinder QEC depending on structure; in HMC they are small, retarded, and structured (KMS/FDT, Sec.~\ref{sec:influence}), yielding predictable, benign deviations. We illustrate this with a QEC-oriented toy diagnostic:

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\vspace{0.5em}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    width=0.8\textwidth,
    height=0.5\textwidth,
    xlabel={Lag $\Delta u$ (steps)},
    ylabel={$g^{(2)}(\Delta u)$},
    grid=major,
    legend style={at={(0.02,0.98)},anchor=north west}
