\end{figure}

\subsection{Repetition-Code Robustness under Correlated Temporal Noise}
We consider a 5-qubit repetition code subject to correlated bit-flip noise across time (a binary Markov model with mean error rate $p$ and lag-1 correlation coefficient $\rho$). Majority decoding yields entanglement fidelity $F_e \approx 1 - P_L$, where $P_L$ is the logical error probability. Figure~\ref{fig:qec_rep} shows $F_e$ vs $(\rho,p)$; as expected, stronger temporal correlations degrade $F_e$, but the effect is modest for small $p$ in the gentle regime. This toy diagnostic captures the essence of \emph{quantum error correlations} introduced by HMC’s memory kernel: weak, retarded, and structured correlations compatible with reliable decoding on late radiation windows.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\vspace{0.5em}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    width=0.8\textwidth,
    height=0.5\textwidth,
